    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "oh okay thats good to know. so basically the money just sits there in the middle? i'm a bit nervous about just letting a third party hold onto a large chunk of my savings. who actually controls the money while it's in there and how do they decide when to release it to the seller?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "The escrow agent is a neutral third party, chosen by the parties involved in the transaction, to hold the funds. They typically have a set of rules and guidelines to follow, which are outlined in the purchase agreement. The escrow agent will review the property taxes and insurance payments, ensuring they're up to date, and hold the funds until the next payment period. Once the funds are verified, the escrow agent will release the funds to the relevant parties, which in this case, would be the local government for property taxes and the insurance company. The escrow agent is typically independent, but they may have to follow the rules set by the government and insurance companies.",
